	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Wheat price drives up FAO food price index to a two-year high</h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to FAO, ‘surging wheat prices drove international food prices up 5% last month in the biggest month-on-month increase since November 2009.’ The 2010 wheat crop, at 646 million tonnes, is down 5% on 2009 levels, but still the third largest harvest ever. While wheat stocks are down 9%, this is from a level which had reached an eight-year high.</p><p>The increase in wheat prices has driven the FAO food price index ‘up to its highest level since September 2008’. However this is still ‘38% down from its peak in June 2008’.</p><p>While the FAO is forecasting that coarse grain production will be 6 million tonnes down from earlier predictions, this is still marginally above the production levels achieved in 2009, the second largest harvest on record.</p><p>Overall the latest FAO update shows that ‘the forecast for world cereal production in 2010 has been lowered by 41 million tonnes to 2,238 million tonnes from 2,279 million tonnes reported in June’. Output is nevertheless projected to be ‘the third highest on record and above the five-year average’.</p><p>According to FAO, ‘under the present forecast, world cereal utilisation would slightly exceed production in 2010/11. This would trigger a 2% contraction in world ending stocks [i.e., the total volume of wheat stocks held across the globe] from their 8-year-high opening levels, and a small decline in world cereal stocks-to-use ratio.’ However the stocks-to-use ratio is still 23% substantially above the 19.5% low witnessed in the 2007/08 food crisis period.</p><p>The continuing surge in wheat prices took many traders by surprise, and not just agricultural commentators. Many analysts find the recent price increases hard to justify in the face of ample world supplies. On the wheat market, for example, while Russia has halted exports due to high temperatures and a severe drought, and Canada has been hit by floods, Australian production has recovered after a severe drought while good crops are expected in the United States. Overall, therefore, no absolute shortage is expected. Against this background, the FAO is to devote a special one-day session to examining ‘the recent disturbances in world cereal markets’.</p><p>According to Reuters reports, in the light of developments on world cereals markets, French President Sarkozy is to use his position as chair of the G20 to call for an examination of ways to ‘curb excessive exchange rate and commodity price volatility’. He described the volatility of which the current wheat price surge is indicative as ‘highly destructive’, and called for similar regulation to that applied to financial derivatives. Analysts suggest that while ‘unbridled speculation’ on grain markets did not provoke rising wheat prices, it ‘has considerably accelerated’ price increases. Analysts at German campaigning NGO Germanwatch claim that ‘investors have exploited weak supply stemming from extreme regional climate conditions, which is nonetheless not dramatic on a global scale, by buying huge volumes of grain futures and heating up grain markets.’</p><p>The political knock-on effects of rising wheat prices have already been seen in the ACP, with food riots in Mozambique leading to fatalities.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
