<a href="http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/45006/icode/" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/45006/icode/</a></p><p><i>Reuters</i>, ‘France to press G20 to curb currency swings – Sarkozy’, 25 August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSPISPJE63820100825" target="_blank">www.reuters.com/article/idUSPISPJE63820100825</a></p><p>Business Day, ‘Tense Maputo counts cost of violent price riots’, 3 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201009030649.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201009030649.html</a></p><p><i>Xinhuanet</i>, ‘Riots against price rises spread to central province of Manica in Mozambique’, 4 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://english.souslemanguier.com/nouvelles/news.asp?id=11&amp;pays=253&amp;idnews=26495" target="_self">http://english.souslemanguier.com/nouvelles/news.asp?id=11&amp;pays=253&...</a></p><p>German Watch, ‘Germanwatch fordert Regulierung der Spekulation an den Europäischen Getreidebörsen’, 23 August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.germanwatch.org/" target="_self">http://www.germanwatch.org/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The current situation in the wheat market is quite unlike the situation when prices peaked in 2007 and early 2008. Indeed, wheat prices in June 2010 were at their lowest since 2005, as stocks were high due to increased production stimulated by earlier high prices. The unanticipated surge in wheat prices may well see G20 members from the global South supporting President Sarkozy’s call for global action to regulate speculation in basic food commodities. Under the leadership of Commissioner Michel Barnier, Commissioner for the Internal Market, the European Commission is understood to be consulting extensively on a possible initiative to strengthen regulation of European commodity markets, with a public conference being convened in Brussels on 21 September.</p><p>Within Europe, commodities regulation was previously considered a national responsibility, but many Europeans – and not only the French – consider that it was pursued half-heartedly at best in the UK, where most of the main European markets are (although milling wheat futures are traded in Paris). In the present circumstances, the UK may find it difficult to mobilise European allies willing to join them in resisting tighter regulation of speculative trading in commodity markets.</p><p>Policy initiatives to curb speculation and reduce volatility in markets for basic food commodities would bring considerable benefits to net food-importing countries in the ACP. In addition, effective action to curb speculation could also provide a more stable environment for the development of national agricultural development strategies in ACP countries and the pursuit of common regional agricultural trade policies in the various ACP regions. This could then open up scope for the commercially sustainable introduction of agricultural innovations which would serve to better insulate diverse ACP regions from the worst effects of climate change.</p>
		</div>
		
